<DOC><DOCNO> AP880629-0079 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0608EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-29 0589</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0607</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Bring Some Welcome Relief</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms and cooler weather soothed parts of thedrought-parched central United States early today, after setting atleast one record for rainfall.   Madison, Wis., received 1.67 inches of rain on Tuesday, breakinga 60-year-old mark of 1.62 inches.   Despite a break in the 100-degree temperatures, health officialsin St. Louis reported another death Tuesday from Saturday's torridheat. An 87-year-old woman died of heat stroke, bringing to ninethe number of weather-related deaths there in a recent heat wave.   In Colorado, a flash flood warning was issued Tuesday night forparts of Gunnison County as the Ohio Creek flooded its banks andwater up to 4 feet deep surrounded homes north of Gunnison.   Other heavy rainfall totals early today included 3.1 inches atOklahoma City, 2.14 inches at La Crosse, Wis., and 1.19 inches atLaramie, Wyo.   Severe weather accompanied the rain in some areas. Thunderstormsin northwestern Oklahoma produced gusts to 62 mph that downedtrees. Strong thunderstorm winds also downed tree limbs and damageda mobile home and a barn.   A thunderstorm in eastern Nebraska hurled gusts to 65 mph, whilethunderstorms in Montana dropped golf ball-size hail.   Scattered showers and thunderstorms extended from the highPlains to the middle Mississippi Valley early today, withthunderstorms most numerous in eastern Nebraska and western Iowa,two of the states worst hit by the drought.   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms also dampened theRocky Mountain region, the Northeast and the Florida peninsula.   The heat wave continued to break, with temperatures dropping tothe 40s and 50s in the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakesregion and the northeastern states early today. Highs were in the80s in parts of Kansas, Missouri, Iowa and Nebraska.   The forecast for today called for widespread showers andthunderstorms from the northern Rockies through the Missouri Valleyinto the middle Mississippi Valley and Florida; showers and a fewthunderstorms scattered over much of New England; and mostly sunnyskies over the rest of the rest of the nation.   High temperatures were expected in the 60s from the upper GreatLakes through the upper Ohio Valley into New England; in the 70sfrom the upper Mississippi Valley into the lower Ohio Valley andnorthern sections of the Middle Atlantic Coast region; in the 60sand 70s in the Pacific Northwest; 100 to 105 degrees across partsof the lower Mississippi Valley, the plains of the Rio GrandeValley, the northern California valleys and the desert Southwest;and in the 80s or 90s across the rest of the nation.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 36degrees at Sexton Summit, Ore., to 90 degrees at Las Vegas, Nev.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 74 fair; Boston 65 partly cloudy; Buffalo 48fair; Charleston, S.C. 66 fair; Cincinnati 69 cloudy; Cleveland 60fair; Detroit 59 fair; Miami 80 fair; New York 72 partly cloudy;Philadelphia 72 cloudy; Pittsburgh 62 partly cloudy; Portland,Maine 62 cloudy; Washington 74 cloudy.   _Central: Bismarck 66 fair; Chicago 62 showery; Dallas-FortWorth 77 fair; Denver 71 cloudy; Des Moines 82 thunderstorm;Indianapolis 69 fair; Kansas City 84 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St.Paul 65 cloudy; Nashville 71 fair; New Orleans 81 hazy; St. Louis79 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 62 fair; Anchorage 55 fair; Las Vegas 90windy; Los Angeles 65 partly cloudy; Phoenix 87 fair; Salt LakeCity 76 cloudy; San Diego 64 fair; San Francisco 55 windy; Seattle52 cloudy.   _Canada: Montreal 41 fair; Toronto 43 fair.</TEXT></DOC>